n": {"begin": 928, "end": 937}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7052"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tissue transglutaminase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9856117963790894, "span": {"begin": 962, "end": 985}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3120"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9661130309104919, "span": {"begin": 1052, "end": 1059}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3130"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ8 molecules", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9595667719841003, "span": {"begin": 1063, "end": 1080}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "APCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9046745300292969, "span": {"begin": 1105, "end": 1109}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "APCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7712863087654114, "span": {"begin": 1193, "end": 1197}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dendritic cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.865488588809967, "span": {"begin": 1206, "end": 1221}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3118"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ2/8 molecules", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.980189323425293, "span": {"begin": 1285, "end": 1304}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:920"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Gluten-specific CD4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9659717679023743, "span": {"begin": 1307, "end": 1326}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "+ T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6891124844551086, "span": {"begin": 1326, "end": 1335}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002446", "mim:212750"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "celiac disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999992847442627, "span": {"begin": 1409, "end": 1423}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "peptide-MHC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7474884986877441, "span": {"begin": 1441, "end": 1452}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:445347"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "T-cell receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969457983970642, "span": {"begin": 1473, "end": 1489}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6962"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TCRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9980922937393188, "span": {"begin": 1491, "end": 1495}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "gluten-reactive T cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6811614036560059, "span": {"begin": 1593, "end": 1616}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002446", "mim:212750"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "gluten", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8952720761299133, "span": {"begin": 1593, "end": 1599}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "APCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.619870662689209, "span": {"begin": 1637, "end": 1641}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.58302241563797, "span": {"begin": 1708, "end": 1709}}, {"id": ["CL:0000084"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8606231212615967, "span": {"begin": 1708, "end": 1714}}, {"id": ["CL:0000084"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T-cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.767914354801178, "span": {"begin": 1804, "end": 1810}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002446", "mim:212750"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "celiac disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999992847442627, "span": {"begin": 1920, "end": 1934}}], "text": "Professional antigen-presenting cells, like dendritic cells, survey the body for the presence of pathogens (Banchereau and&nbsp;Steinman, 1998;&nbsp;Steinman, 2007). Their phagocytic properties endow them with the capacity to endocytose and process such pathogens and bind peptides derived thereof to HLA molecules for presentation to antigen-specific T cells (van der Most et al., 1996; Cella et al., 1997). Upon encounter with pathogens, the dendritic cells migrate to the local organized lymphoid structures where the priming of naive T cells by the antigen-loaded dendritic cells takes place (Banchereau &amp; Steinman, 1998; Koni et al., 2001; Jenkins, 2017).  In the context of celiac disease, the relevant antigen is gluten, a protein complex found in wheat and related cereals. After ingestion, gluten is partially digested in the gastrointestinal tract, and specific peptides&mdash;especially those rich in proline and glutamine&mdash;are deamidated by tissue transglutaminase. These deamidated peptides have an increased binding affinity for HLA-DQ2 or HLA-DQ8 molecules, which are expressed by APCs in genetically susceptible individuals (Sollid, 2002). Upon uptake and processing, APCs such as dendritic cells present these immunodominant gluten peptides in the context of HLA-DQ2/8 molecules.  Gluten-specific CD4+ T cells, which are expanded in the intestinal lamina propria of individuals with celiac disease, recognize these peptide-MHC complexes via their T-cell receptors (TCRs) (Abadie et al., 2011). This antigen-specific recognition promotes the stable co-localization of gluten-reactive T cells with the presenting APCs, enabling the formation of immunological synapses that facilitate T cell activation. The interaction triggers a cascade of downstream immune responses, including T-cell proliferation and cytokine production, which drive the pathogenic adaptive immune response characteristic of celiac disease (Setty et al., 2008; van de Wal et al., 1998).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:10:48 +0000 2026"}